The level of military engagement in Syria has already been acceleration on the Middle East agenda given France's rapid response in launching a series of airstrikes on Raqqa, the de facto capital of the Islamic State. President Hollande's description of the attacks as an "act of war" could also be significant, if it is the precursor to invoking NATO's Article V, which would essentially mandate all treaty members to back France, as British Prime Minister David Cameron already told the BBC Monday his wish to extend his country's military involvement.
